## Commands Used

| Command | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `ssh user@host -p PORT` | Connect to remote host via SSH on non-default port |
| `ls` | List contents of current directory |
| `cat filename` | Print file contents to terminal |

---

## What Went Smoothly

Connection was straightforward once the non-standard port flag was identified. The `-p` flag is easy to overlook if you default to assuming port 22 — worth making a habit of always checking specified port requirements before connecting.

---

## Real-World Pentest Application

**SSH on non-standard ports** is extremely common in real environments. During an Nmap scan on an engagement, services running on unexpected ports are high-value findings — administrators often move SSH to a non-standard port thinking it reduces attack surface (security through obscurity). It doesn't prevent exploitation but it does mean you need to run full port range scans (`nmap -p-`) to find it.

**`cat` for credential harvesting** — reading files in home directories and common locations (`/home`, `/root`, `/var/www`, `/etc`) is a core post-exploitation habit. Configuration files, `.bash_history`, `.ssh/authorized_keys`, and credential files are frequently found this way after gaining initial access.

---

## Key Takeaway

The `-p` flag for SSH is the only non-obvious piece of this level. The real lesson is building the habit of reading challenge requirements carefully before connecting — missing a port specification, a username, or a protocol detail in a real engagement wastes time and creates noise in logs.

